# Data and Label Integrity

Apply when editing data ingestion, normalization, timeline, label generation, split logic, or their tests.

## Required Guarantees
- Preserve provenance from raw source through canonical events and labels.
- Enforce strict as-of-time slicing for all derived features and episode context.
- Keep these artifacts strictly separate:
  - trigger labels
  - observed clinician actions
  - protocol-derived gold actions
- Fail loudly on ambiguous mappings or timestamps; no silent fallback/default mapping.
- For **sustained-condition triggers** (e.g. hypotension sustained MAP < 65 for 15 minutes), treat label validity as potentially sensitive to **measurement frequency**. If using “consecutive readings” or “unbroken tail” logic, add validation that the signal is sampled densely enough (or explicitly encode a minimum sampling density / maximum allowed gaps) and reflect this in tests and audit outputs.

## Required Tests
- Leakage tests (future access attempts fail).
- Schema stability tests for core benchmark artifacts.
- Split safety tests proving patient-level leakage prevention.
- Real-data integration tests must not silently skip when real MIMIC data is present on disk (e.g., repo-local `physionet.org/files/mimiciv/<version>/`). Prefer auto-discovery over “env var required” gating.
- When completing a new phase, extend the real-data end-to-end integration test to exercise that phase’s new public contract (even if only as a minimal “smoke gate” using real episodes/timelines).

## Change Discipline
- If episode semantics, trigger logic, or action mapping changes:
  - update relevant docs
  - update audit artifacts
  - regenerate or revalidate affected outputs
